[src:web-workers/using-web-workers] The worker thread is killed immediately.
[src:web-workers/using-web-workers] When a runtime error occurs in the worker, its `onerror` event handler is called.
[src:web-workers/using-web-workers] It receives an event named `error` which implements the `ErrorEvent` interface.
[src:web-workers/using-web-workers] The event doesn't bubble and is cancelable; to prevent the default action from taking place, the worker can call the error event's `preventDefault()` method.
[src:web-workers/using-web-workers] The name of the script file in which the error occurred.
[src:web-workers/using-web-workers] The line number of the script file on which the error occurred.
[src:web-workers/using-web-workers] Workers may spawn more workers if they wish.
[src:web-workers/using-web-workers] So-called sub-workers must be hosted within the same origin as the parent page.
[src:web-workers/using-web-workers] Also, the URIs for subworkers are resolved relative to the parent worker's location rather than that of the owning page.
[src:web-workers/using-web-workers] This makes it easier for workers to keep track of where their dependencies are.
[src:web-workers/using-web-workers] Worker threads have access to a global function, `importScripts()`, which lets them import scripts.
[src:web-workers/using-web-workers] The browser loads each listed script and executes it.
[src:web-workers/using-web-workers] Any global objects from each script may then be used by the worker.
[src:web-workers/using-web-workers] If the script can't be loaded, `NETWORK_ERROR` is thrown, and subsequent code will not be executed.
[src:web-workers/using-web-workers] Previously executed code (including code deferred using `setTimeout()`) will still be functional though.
[src:web-workers/using-web-workers] Function declarations **after** the `importScripts()` method are also kept, since these are always evaluated before the rest of the code.
